<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-23T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-23T22:00:00-05:00" n="233" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/297: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-24T12:00:00+09:00">June 24,
                                    1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 24—12:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>294. Our 277 [<hi rend="italic">274</hi>], june 15, 5 p.m. Following
                                informal conversations between the Prime Minister’s<note n="88" xml:id="d233fn88">Baron Kiichiro Hiranuma.</note> personal
                                adviser and the British Ambassador, the Foreign Minister yesterday
                                proposed to the British Ambassador that there be held next week in
                                Tokyo a round table conference to discuss the Tientsin situation and
                                seek solution thereof on a strictly local basis. The proposal has
                                been referred to London.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dooman</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>